{
  "doc_id": "27883",
  "text": "Altered responses to play initiations have previously been reported after neonatal PFC lesions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Lesions of the lateral and ventral OFC have been found to disrupt the partner-related modulation of play [CITATION_5] . Thus, control but not lesioned rats respond differently to dominant, subordinate, and female rats. Animals with medial PFC lesions still show partnerrelated changes in social play behavior, but they use less complex defensive strategies [CITATION_6] ). These, and other, studies indicate that after neonatal PFC lesions, play behavior is still observed but that its structure and sensitivity to social cues is altered [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . In the present study, however, the effect of temporary PFC inactivation was more substantial and, in contrast to the neonatal lesion studies, play initiations (ie, pouncing) were markedly reduced.",
